<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-02-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-02-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="112" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d112">
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">No. 15.</seg></opener>
                            <head><persName type="from">Mr. Hammond</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr. Elliot</persName>.</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Foreign Office,</hi></placeName>
                                    <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-02-05"><hi rend="italic">February</hi> 5, 1864.</date></dateline></opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I am directed by Earl Russell to
                                transmit to you, to be laid before the Duke of Newcastle, the
                                accompanying copy of a letter from Messrs. Sinclair, Hamilton &amp;
                                Co., stating their reasons for believing Penguin island to be
                                British territory; and I am to request that you will move his grace
                                to inform Lord Russell what answer should be returned to Messrs.
                                Sinclair, Hamilton &amp; Co.</p>
                            <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>E. HAMMOND.</signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>